{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Alberto Campagnolo trained as a book conservator (in Spoleto, Italy) and has worked in that capacity in various institutions, including the London Metropolitan Archives, St. Catherine\u8217's Monastery (Egypt), and the Vatican Library.He studied Conservation of Library Materials at Ca\u8217' Foscari University Venice, and holds an MA in Digital Culture and Technology from King\u8217's College London. He pursued a{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "ualresearchonline.arts.ac.uk/8749/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
\u160?PhD on an automated visualization of historical bookbinding structures
}}}
\u160?at the\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http/www.ligatus.org.uk/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Ligatus Research Centre
}}}
\u160?({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.arts.ac.uk/chelsea/research/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
University of the Arts, London
}}}
).In July 2016, he has been appointed as{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.clir.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
\u160?CLIR
}}}
/{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.clir.orgdlf"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
DLF
}}}
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.clir.orgfellowships/postdoc/applicants/library-of-congress-preservation-research-and-testing-division-prtd"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
\u160?Postdoctoral Fellow in Data Curation for Medieval Studies at the Library of Congress
}}}
\u160?(Washington, DC).Alberto has served on the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://digitalmedievalist.wordpress.com/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Digital Medievalist
}}}
 board since 2014, first as Deputy Director, and as Director since 2015.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Alexandrina is a game designer, community-based researcher, and media artist who believes in the possibilities of the decolonial imaginary using digital media as an emancipatory tool._x000D__x000D_ _x000D__x000D_ She is an Assistant Professor of Interactive Media and Game Development at Worcester Polytechnic Institute. Her most recent game,\u160?{\i The Resisters}, was an alternate reality game she designed through participatory research with young people of color about local social movement history in Providence, RI. Before joining WPI, she earned her Ph.D. from the Annenberg School for Communication and Journalism at the University of Southern California and an M.A. from the\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "ethnicstudies.sfsu.edu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
College of Ethnic Studies
}}}
\u160?at San Francisco State University\u8212-the only autonomous institution of its kind in the United States\u8212-where she researched adolescent girls of color and their race and gender identity development through online doll play. Alexandrina blends her knowledge of the digital with an aesthetic sense of tactile design; some of her past work includes designing a collection of dresses made entirely from recycled goods as a benefit for a cancer wellness nonprofit._x000D__x000D_ _x000D__x000D_ Alexandrina utilizes principles of self-determination and relevant education in her teaching and research. She teaches at university and high school levels, and specializes in digital media skill building with young people of color.\u160?She is a co-chair of Situated Critical Race + Media (SCR+M!) of\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "femtechnet.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
FemTechNet
}}}
, a multi-university collaborative feminist technology organization. She is the Futurist for the Latinx Pacific Archive and is working on developing a line of ovulation-tracking jewelry that is both affordable and flawlessly stylish. As a community-based researcher and participatory designer, her speculative work is still anchored in lived experience.\u160?She works closely with{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "newurbanarts.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
\u160?New Urban Arts
}}}
, a youth art studio and imagination incubator. Alexandrina uses critical pedagogy and community-based research as platforms to work with institutions, community organizations, researchers, and artists. Her research has received funding from the National Science Foundation,\u160?the National Endowment for the Humanities, the Andrew W. Mellon Foundation-John E. Sawyer Seminars, the Teagle Foundation, the Rhode Island Council of the Humanities,\u160?and the Voqal Fund.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Alexis Lothian is a interdisciplinary scholar of queer and feminist media and cultural studies with a focus on speculative fiction, digital media, and online fandom. She lives in the Washington, DC area and is\u160?a tenure track Assistant Professor of\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "wmst.umd.edu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Women\u8217's Studies\u160?
}}}
at University of Maryland College Park, where she teaches in the\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "lgbts.umd.edu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
LGBT Studies
}}}
\u160?program and the undergraduate honors program in\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "dcc.umd.edu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Design | Culture and Creativity.
}}}
_x000D_ _x000D_ Lothian is presently developing a book manuscript based on her PhD dissertation, \u8220"Deviant Futures: Speculative Fiction and Queer Time,\u8221" while also working on what will become a second monograph on critical and social justice-oriented fan cultures and participating in collaborative work as part of the TransformDH collective. Read more on her\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.queergeektheory.orgwordpress/dissertatio/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
research page
}}}
._x000D_ _x000D_ Lothian is also a participant in feminist science fiction and media fandom, with a specific interest in the ways fan communities engage in critical theorizing and activism (for example, through\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "journal.transformativeworks.orgindex.php/twc/article/view/172/119"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
online discussion
}}}
\u160?and\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "lstein.wordpress.com/2010/06/03/participatory-cultures-and-vidding-a-virtual-rendition-of-our-digital-media-and-learning-2010-workshop-2/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
fan video
}}}
). She uses some of these forms in\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "queergeektheory.orgvidding"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
her own scholarly work
}}}
, in addition to standard academic practices.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 \u8203?Alison Langmead holds a joint faculty appointment between the Dietrich School of Arts and Sciences and the School of Computing and Information at the University of Pittsburgh. She teaches and researches in the field of the digital humanities, focusing especially on applying digital methods mindfully within the context of visual and material culture studies._x000D__x000D_ _x000D__x000D_ For the Department of Art History and Architecture, Alison serves as the Director of the Visual Media Workshop (VMW). The mission of the VMW is to develop and encourage the creation of innovative methods for producing, disseminating, and preserving the academic work using digital technologies as a fundamental component of our scholarly toolkit. To achieve these objectives, she directs a technologically-focused environment of collaboration and creativity where students and faculty from a number of departments across the University come together to work on projects that apply digital methods and techniques with focus and intention._x000D__x000D_ _x000D__x000D_ For the School of Computing and Information (SCI), Alison researches the relationship between the historical practice of information management and digital computing, both as a historical narrative and also as a complex, changing process in contemporary America. This research, plus all of the theories, concepts, and models that she teaches at SCI, are put into daily practice in her work directing the VMW._x000D__x000D_ _x000D__x000D_ In terms of teaching, Alison teaches courses in digital preservation and the digital humanities, especially, but not exclusively, at the graduate level.Alison is also the principal contact for the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.dhrx.pitt.edu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
DHRX: Digital Humanities Research at Pitt
}}}
 initiative, which represents a transdisciplinary network of scholars here at the University of Pittsburgh who use digital methods to study the ways in which humans interact with their environments, whether social or cultural, natural or human-created.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 {\b Amanda French} is currently Research Assistant Professor and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "thatcamp.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
THATCamp
}}}
 Coordinator at the Roy Rosenzweig {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "chnm.gmu.edu"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Center for History and New Media
}}}
 at George Mason University, helping scholars worldwide organize their own version of The Humanities and Technology Camp, \u8220"an inexpensive, open meeting where humanists and technologists of all skill levels learn and build together in sessions proposed on the spot.\u8221" Before that, she was an Assistant Research Scholar in the Archives and Public History program at New York University, where she helped develop a model curriculum emphasizing digital skills, and where she developed and taught the graduate course \u8220"{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "aphdigital.orgclasses/G572033F09/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Creating Digital History
}}}
.\u8221" Before that, French taught graduate and undergraduate courses in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "eng560.wordpress.com"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Victorian poetry and poetics
}}}
, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "wikis.lib.ncsu.edu/index.php//files/ENG_463"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
the Victorian period
}}}
, and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "hon296a.wordpress.com/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
academic research methods for the digital age
}}}
 as a Teaching Assistant Professor at North Carolina State University. She held the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.clir.orgfellowships/postdoc/postdoc.html"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Council on Library and Information Resources Postdoctoral Fellowship
}}}
 from 2004 to 2006.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Amanda Visconti was MITH's Winnemore Digital Dissertation Fellow for 2014-2015 and holds a Ph.D in Literature from the University of Maryland; she also holds a master's with a specialization in digital humanities HCI from the University of Michigan School of Information. Visconti recently completed\u160?a digital dissertation with an innovative format and methodology: scholarly blogging, design, coding, user-testing, and a journal article, rather than the traditional proto-monograph. She regularly blogs about her dissertation at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.literaturegeek.com/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
LiteratureGeek.com
}}}
 and tweets\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.twitter.com/Literature_Geek"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
@Literature_Geek
}}}
. An active member of the digital humanities community, Visconti's DH activity includes co-organizing a THATCamp (the inaugural THATCamp Games), receiving an ACH Microgrant for information visualization of knowledge flow in Digital Humanities Quarterly, and invited attendance at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "codespeak.scholarslab.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Speaking in Code
}}}
 and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "oneweekonetool.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
One Week | One Tool
}}}
. She is also a professional web developer who has served in three past digital archives, web development, and usability roles at MITH.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Avery Dame currently serves as {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "mith.umd.edu/community/fellowships/winnemore-fellows/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
MITH Winnemore Digital Dissertation Fellow
}}}
 for 2016-2017. He is a Ph.D. candidate in Women\u8217's Studies at the University of Maryland, College Park. Avery received his BA (2010) in English from the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "english.ua.edu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
University of Alabama
}}}
, Tuscaloosa, and his MA (2012) in American Studies from {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "americanstudies.ku.edu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
the University of Kansas
}}}
. His work has appeared in the {\i Journal of Language and Sexuality}, {\i Critical Studies in Media Communication}, and {\i TSQ: Transgender Studies Quarterly}, and he served as Assistant Editor of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://journals.ku.edu/index.php/amerstud"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
{\i AMSJ: American Studies}
}}}
 from 2010 to 2012._x000D__x000D_ _x000D__x000D_ His research interests include new media, sociolinguistics, gender and transgender studies, and discourse analysis. While at UMD, his dissertation work {\i Talk Amongst Yourselves: Conceptions of \u8220"Community\u8221" in Transgender Counterpublic Discourse Online, 1990 \u8211- 2014},\u160?explores the affective and structural meanings assigned to \u8220"community\u8221" in English-language transgender discourse online. Drawing on a variety of historic and contemporary sites, he\u160?analyzes how users past and present construct \u8220"transgender community\u8221" in discourse\u8212-constructions shaped by different platform-specific affordances. His MITH project focuses on building a searchable archive of two major transgender Usenet groups, alt.transgendered and soc.support.transgender, amongst the few archival sites where the term \u8220"cisgender\u8221" is used._x000D__x000D_ _x000D__x000D_ Avery\u8217's teaching also brings his focus on technology into the classroom. He has developed student projects focused on adding coverage for underrepresented subjects and groups on Wikipedia; You can see some of his students\u8217' pages {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wikiedu.orgblog/2015/03/09/the-roundup-women-and-art-part-2/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
highlighted by the Wiki Education Foundation here
}}}
. He has also led Game Design workshops for the Design Cultures & Creativity program at UMD.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Bernard Frischer is a leading virtual archaeologist and the author of seven printed books, three e-books, and dozens of articles on virtual heritage, Classics, and the survival of the Classical world. He is the founding editor of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.journals.elsevier.com/digital-applications-in-archaeology-and-cultural-heritage/news/editor-in-chief-introduces-the-journal/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Digital Applications in Archaeology and Cultural Heritage
}}}
, an innovative online, peer-reviewed journal where scientists can publish interactive 3D models.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 {\b Bethany Nowviskie} is Director of Digital Research & Scholarship at the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "lib.virginia.edu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
University of Virginia Library
}}}
, Associate Director of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "uvasci.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Scholarly Communication Institute
}}}
, and President of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "ach.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Association for Computers and the Humanities
}}}
 (ACH). In addition to leading the ACH, she is a steering committee member for {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "digitalhumanities.orgcenternet/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
centerNet
}}}
 (the international organization of digital humanities centers) and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "mediacommons.futureofthebook.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
MediaCommons
}}}
, and chair of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "mla.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
MLA
}}}
\u8216's Committee on Information Technology. At UVa, she represents the Library on the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.virginia.edu/generalfacultycouncil/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
General Faculty Council
}}}
.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 {\b Bill Ferster}\u160?directs the\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.viseyes.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
VisualEyes Project
}}}
\u160?at the University of Virginia with a joint faculty appointment with the Center for Technology and Teacher Education at the Curry School of Education, and with the \u160?Sciences, Humanities & Arts Technology Initiative (SHANTI) \u160?at the College of Arts and Sciences._x000D_ _x000D_ In past lives, he founded StageTools, a leading developer of digital motion control tools with its MovingPicture product; Editing Machines, EMMY award winning developer of the first digital nonlinear editing system; and West End, a pioneer in PC-based animation and presentation graphics tools.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 _x000D__x000D_\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 _x000D__x000D_ _x000D__x000D_ Byron Hawk is an Associate Professor of English at George Mason University. His research interests are histories and theories of composition, rhetorical theory and technology, and rhetorics of popular music. He is the author of {\i A Counter-History of Composition: Toward Methodologies of Complexity\u160?}(University of Pittsburgh Press, 2007), which won JAC's W. Ross Winterowd Award._x000D__x000D_ _x000D__x000D_\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 _x000D__x000D_\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 _x000D__x000D_\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 {\b Carla L. Peterson}\u160?is a professor in the\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.english.umd.edu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Department of English
}}}
\u160?at the University of Maryland, and affiliate faculty of the departments of Women\u8217's Studies, American Studies, and African-American Studies. Peterson received her undergraduate degree from Radcliffe College and a Ph.D. in Comparative Literature from Yale University. She is the author of{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "books.google.com/books?id=jrirQL5L0xgC&source=gbs_navlinks_s"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
\u8220"Doers of the Word\u8221": African-American Women Speakers and Writers in the North (1830-1880)
}}}
\u160?(Rutgers University Press, 1998). She has published numerous essays on nineteenth-century African American literature and culture. Her newly published book, titled\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "yalepress.yale.edu/book.asp?isbn=9780300162554"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Black Gotham: A Family History of African Americans in Nineteenth-Century New York City
}}}
\u160?(Yale University Press, 2011), is a social and cultural history of African Americans in nineteenth-century New York City as seen through the lens of family history.\par}

