{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Cheryl Ball studies and teaches rhetorical activities and genres in digital media and publishing contexts, emphasizing how users learn to analyze and produce texts for professional purposes. She calls this apprenticeship philosophy an editorial pedagogy._x000D__x000D_ _x000D__x000D_ Since 2006, she has been editor of the online, peer-reviewed, open-access journal {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "kairos.technorhetoric.net/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Kairos: Rhetoric, Technology, and Pedagogy
}}}
, which exclusively publishes digital media scholarship and is read in 180 countries. The portfolio on {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "ceball.com/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
her website
}}}
 showcases her scholarship and teaching in rhetoric and composition, technical communication, and publishing studies, including articles in Classroom Discourse, Computers and Composition, C&C Online, Fibreculture, Convergence, Programmatic Perspectives, Technical Communication Quarterly, Writing & Pedagogy, and several visual rhetoric and multimodal textbooks._x000D__x000D_ _x000D__x000D_ Her other books include a scholarly multimedia collection The New Work of Composing (co-edited with Debra Journet and Ryan Trauman) and the print-based {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.bedfordstmartins.com/Catalog/product/writerdesigner-firstedition-arola"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
RAW: Reading and Writing New Media
}}}
\u160?(co-edited with Jim Kalmbach). Her newest book, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.bedfordstmartins.com/Catalog/product/writerdesigner-firstedition-arola"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Writer/Designer: A Guide to Making Multimodal Projects
}}}
 (with Kristin Arola and Jenny Sheppard), is available to order from Bedford/St. Martin\u8217's Press.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Henry came to Rice in 1996 from Vassar College, where he had been director of the libraries. As Rice\u8217's vice provost and university librarian, he was responsible for the administration, strategy, policymaking and fundraising for the libraries, the Digital Library Initiative, the Electronic Resource Center (now the Digital Media Center) and, most recently, the Rice University Press. During\u160?2000-04, he served also as vice president and chief information officer, taking on responsibility for administration, planning and policy for information technology services and data application centers and working with faculty and students in support of teaching and research. Henry revived the Rice University Press after a decade-long hiatus, taking advantage of technology to make it the first fully digital university press in the U.S. [{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "news.rice.edu/2007/01/18/university-librarian-henry-leaving-rice/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Source: Rice University Website
}}}
]\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Craig Dietrich\u8217's online work includes {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "calltia.com/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Tenants in Action
}}}
 (TIA), an app that facilitates slum-housing reports to LA city agencies; the Mukurtu Archive and Plateau People\u8217's Web Portal, for which he was the first lead developer; {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "scalar.usc.edu"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Scalar
}}}
, which he co-created with the Alliance for Networking Visual Culture (ANVC); and Tensor, an iTunes-like app for managing content from cultural archives. His offline production includes {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "walkingwallstreet.net/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Walking Wall Street
}}}
, a project that has seen Dietrich find Wall Streets in towns and cities across America; and Occupy Roundtable, which he hosted in Los Angeles lecture-halls.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 {\b Craig Saper} (csaper<at>umbc<dot>edu) is on the faculty of the Language, Literacy, & Culture multi-disciplinary doctoral program at UMBC, and has published widely, and in multimodal formats, on the digital humanities. \u160?He is the author of\u160?{\i Intimate Bureaucracies}\u160?(2012),\u160?{\i Networked Art}\u160?(2001) and\u160?{\i Artificial Mythologies\u160?}(1997). He has edited, and written afterwards for, Bob Brown\u8217's\u160?{\i Words}\u160?and\u160?{\i The Readies}\u160?(both 2009), and he edited, with C. J. Freeman and W. Garrett-Petts, an anthology on\u160?{\i Imaging Place}\u160?(2009). He has guest edited special issues of\u160?{\i Visible Language}\u160?(1988) and\u160?{\i Style}(2001), and co-edited, with Ellen Berry, a special issue of\u160?{\i Rhizomes}\u160?on \u8220"Drifts\u8221" (2007), and, with R. Burt, on \u8220"posthumography\u8221" (2010). He is also the reviews editor and \u8220"Blog Report\u8221" columnist for\u160?{\i Rhizomes}. He wrote the introduction to Sharon Kivland\u8217's\u160?{\i A Disturbance of Memory}, II (2008). His curatorial projects include exhibits on \u8220"Assemblings\u8221" (1997), \u8220"Noigandres: Concrete Poetry in Brazil\u8221" (1988), \u8220"TypeBound\u8221" (2008), and\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.folkvine.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
folkvine.org
}}}
\u160?(2003-6). He\u160?is presently completing a biography of a poet-publisher-inventor-impresario-writer in every imaginable genre, Bob Brown, who invented a reading machine. A\u160?{\i New York Times}\u160?Books section Back Page Essay described Saper\u8217's research and publications on Brown in the context of new iPad\u8217's and e-readers, and called Brown the \u8220"godfather of the e-reader.\u8221" An example of Brown\u8217's machine:\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.readies.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
www.readies.org
}}}
.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Cohen is a Professor of History in the\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "chnm.gmu.edu/historyarthistory/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Department of History and Art History
}}}
 at\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.gmu.edu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
George Mason University
}}}
 and the Director of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "chnm.gmu.edu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Roy Rosenzweig Center for History and New Media
}}}
. His personal research has been in digital humanities, broadly construed: the impact of new media and technology on all aspects of knowledge, from the nature of digitized resources to twenty-first century research techniques and software tools to the changing landscape of communication and publication._x000D__x000D_ _x000D__x000D_ He's the\u160?co-author of \u160?{\i Digital History: A Guide to Gathering, Preserving, and Presenting the Past on the Web} (University of Pennsylvania Press, 2005), and the author of {\i Equations from God: Pure Mathematics and Victorian Faith} (Johns Hopkins University Press, 2007).\u160?He has\u160?published articles and book chapters on new media, the history of mathematics and religion, the teaching of history, scholarly communication, and the future of the humanities in a digital age in journals such as the {\i Journal of American History}, {\i Victorian Studies}, and {\i Rethinking History}. Cohen's\u160?work and thought has {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.nytimes.com/2010/08/24/arts/24peer.html"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
been
}}}
 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.nytimes.com/2010/12/04/books/04victorian.html?pagewanted=all"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
featured
}}}
 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.nytimes.com/2011/08/18/books/old-bailey-trials-are-tabulated-for-scholars-online.html"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
frequently
}}}
 in the {\i New York Times,} the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/05/05/AR2010050505309.html"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
{\i Washington Post}
}}}
, the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "chronicle.com/article/Whats-the-Big-Idea-/124277/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
{\i Chronicle of Higher Education}
}}}
, and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?sectioncode=26&storycode=411899&c=1"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
{\i Times Higher Education}
}}}
.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 A graduate of the Hebrew University of Jerusalem (2001), Daniel St\u246?kl Ben Ezra is research professor of Ancient Hebrew and Aramaic since 2011. His main work concerns Dead Sea Scrolls (Qumran, Stuttgart: UTB 2016) and early Rabbinic literature ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "editions.erabbinica.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
editions.erabbinica.org
}}}
 with Hayim Lapin) as well as Jewish-Christian relations: Impact of Yom Kippur on Early Christianity (T\u252?bingen: Mohr-Siebeck 2003). He has been director of the digital humanities programme at the EPHE (2013-2018) and is currently director of the Scripta-num\u233?rique project of PSL creating a VRE combining AI (computer vision, NLP, machine learning) and DH for the studying of manuscripts and inscriptions.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 {\b David McClure} is the Web Applications Specialist on the Scholars\u8217' Lab R&D team. David graduated from Yale University with a degree in the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.yale.edu/humanities/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Humanities
}}}
 in 2009 and worked as an independent web developer in San Francisco, New York, and Madison, Wisconsin before joining the lab in 2011. David is working on the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "neatline.scholarslab.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Omeka + Neatline
}}}
 project and pursuing research projects that explore the idea that software can be used as a tool to inform, extend, and advance traditional lines of inquiry in literary theory and aesthetics.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 {\b Donald Brinkman}\u160?manages external programs in digital humanities, digital heritage and games for learning at Microsoft Research. Donald supports the\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "g4li.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Games for Learning Institute
}}}
, a consortium of 8 universities, 14 principal investigators, and a small army of graduate students whose mission is to explore what makes games fun, what makes them educational, and how to best blend the two goals. He is the Microsoft champion for the\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "play.rit.edu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Just Press Play
}}}
\u160?project, an experiment to transform the undergraduate education of 750 students at Rochester Institute of Technology into a gameful narrative. Other projects include\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "blogs.msdn.com/b/surface/archive/2010/04/27/experience-the-garibaldi-panorama-on-surface.aspx"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Project Garibaldi
}}}
\u160?and\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.gameshownyc.com/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Game Show NYC
}}}
._x000D__x000D_ _x000D__x000D_ Before joining MSR, Donald Brinkman served for two years as a technical program manager for the Microsoft education group. In that role he was responsible for defining vision of innovative business intelligence and analytics for education as well as driving a variety of enterprise-scale server capabilities. Prior to joining Microsoft he spent eight years in developmental and technical roles acquiring and executing government research contracts in areas such as quantum computation; signals intelligence; electromagnetic and kinetic simulations; behavioral economics; game theory; and cross-cultural communications. Donald is a writer, painter, game designer, and a passionate advocate of the benefits of building bridges between technical and humanist disciplines. He is particularly interested in disruptive technologies that leverage crowdsourcing, social computing, culture jamming, transmedia, and other non-traditional approaches. You can find out more about Donald at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "blogs.technet.com/b/next/archive/2012/01/27/donald-brinkman-polymath-poet-gaming-geek.aspx"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Next@Microsoft
}}}
.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Elisa Beshero-Bondar, PhD researches British Romanticism in poetry and drama from the 1790s - 1830s. Her book about women Romantic poets, titled Women, Epic, and Transition in British Romanticism, was published by the University of Delaware Press in 2011, and she has published articles investigating the poetry of Robert Southey, Mary Russell Mitford, and Lord Byron in context with 18th- and 19th-century views of revolution, world empires, natural sciences, and theater productions. She is currently exploring the applications of TEI XML and other markup languages in Digital Humanities research. She is the architect of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "digitalmitford.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Digital Mitford Project
}}}
\u160?and works on other collaborative digital archives and research projects using computational methods to study complicated textual questions, such as {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "amadis.newtfire.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Amadis in Translation
}}}
\u160?and the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://ebeshero.github.io/Pittsburgh_Frankenstein/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Bicentennial Frankenstein Project
}}}
. An active member of the Text Encoding Initiative (TEI), she was elected to serve on from 2016 to 2017 on the TEI Technical Council, an eleven-member international committee that supervises amendments to the TEI Guidelines. A faculty member at Pitt-Greensburg since 2004, she serves as the Director of Pitt-Greensburg's Center for the Digital Text, which supports digital project development and research collaborations among faculty and students.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Elissa Frankle is the Digital Projects Coordinator for Digital Learning and New Media at the United States Holocaust Memorial Museum, where she manages the in-museum digital experience and advocates for the inclusion of visitor voices in the work of the Museum. A longtime cheerleader for citizen history, Elissa served as the community manager for the Holocaust Museum's first citizen history project, {\i Children of the Lodz Ghetto: A Memorial Research Project}, and is the current project lead for {\i History Unfolded: US Newspapers and the Holocaust}, a major citizen history undertaking in support of the Museum's upcoming initiative on Americans and the Holocaust. Outside of work, Elissa serves as the Leadership Development and Awards chair for the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.aam-us.orgresources/professional-networks/edcom"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
American Alliance of Museums' Education Professional Network
}}}
 (EdCom), and organizes the DC chapter of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://twitter.com/museumworkers"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Museum Workers Speak
}}}
, where she fights for paid internships and greater equity in museum labor practices throughout the field.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 _x000D__x000D_\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 \u8203?Emad Khazraee is a sociotechnical information scientists and an assistant professor in the\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.kent.edu/cci"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
college of communication and information
}}}
,\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.kent.edu/slis"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
School of Information
}}}
\u160?at\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.kent.edu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Kent State University
}}}
\u160?and a fellow at\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://cyber.harvard.edu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Berkman-Klein Center for Internet & Society at Harvard
}}}
. His research is formed around the interplay between social and technical phenomena.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 _x000D__x000D_\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 _x000D__x000D_\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 _x000D__x000D_ Khazraee's doctoral research focused on knowledge production processes in data-intensive, collaborative and multidisciplinary communities of practice, specifically the knowledge production processes in archaeological communities of practice. His research also focuses on how archaeologists construct their epistemic narratives from recorded pieces of information, looking at the way they collaborate and the performativity of information technologies.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 _x000D__x000D_\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 _x000D__x000D_\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 In another research trajectory, Khazraee looks at the cultural differences in new media use and the relationship between social change and digital technologies. Relying on sociotechnical approaches to social media studies and conceptual frameworks developed in Science Technology Studies (STS), he explores the role of social media in social transformations.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 _x000D__x000D_\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 _x000D__x000D_\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Khazraee has also held a Post-Doctoral research fellow position at the{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.global.asc.upenn.edu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
\u160?Center for Global Communication Studies
}}}
\u160?at the\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.asc.upenn.edu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Annenberg School for Communication
}}}
\u160?at the\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.upenn.edu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
University of Pennsylvania
}}}
\u160?(2014-2015). He received his Ph.D. in Information Studies from the\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "cci.drexel.edu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
College of Computing and Informatics
}}}
,\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.drexel.edu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Drexel University
}}}
, and a\u160?Master\u8217's Degree in Architecture from the University of Tehran. In addition to practicing as an architect in Iran, he has worked in the preservation of historical monuments and sites before joining the Encyclopaedia of Iranian Architectural History (EIAH) in 2006, where he was the director of the ICT Department (2006-2009), with the goal of creating infrastructure for meaningful integration of information technology into cultural heritage practices.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 {\b Ethan Watrall} is an Assistant Professor in the Department of Anthropology and Associate Director of Matrix: The Center for Humane Arts, Letters & Social Sciences Online ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "matrix.msu.edu"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
matrix.msu.edu
}}}
) at Michigan State University. In addition, Ethan is Director of the Cultural Heritage Informatics Initiative ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "chi.anthropology.msu.edu"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
chi.anthropology.msu.edu
}}}
) and the Cultural Heritage Informatics Fieldschool at Michigan State University ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "sites.matrix.msu.edu/chi-fieldschool"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
sites.matrix.msu.edu/chi-fieldschool
}}}
). Ethan\u8217's interests fall in the domain of cultural heritage informatics and digital archaeology, with particular focus on serious games & meaningful play, mobile & geospatial (mostly within the context of public outreach and engagement), and linked open archaeological data. Ethan is PI of the NEH funded "Red Land/Black Land: Teaching Ancient Egyptian History Through Game-Based Learning\u8221" project.\u160? Ethan is editor of Play the Past ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.playthepast.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
www.playthepast.org
}}}
), a collaborative authored, scholarly blog dedicated to exploring the intersection between games and cultural heritage.\u160? In addition, Ethan is co-editor of Archaeology 2.0: New Tools for Communication and Collaboration, an open access volume published by the UCLA Cotsen Institute of Archaeology Press ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.escholarship.orguc/item/1r6137tb"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
www.escholarship.orguc/item/1r6137tb
}}}
). In addition to his scholarly work, Ethan has written trade books on web and interactive design, including Head First Web Design published by O\u8217'Reilly.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 {\b Dr. Williams} is an Associate Professor of English at the University of South Carolina Upstate where he has led a research project on accessible website development. His research and teaching interests include eighteenth-century studies, orality & literacy, the digital humanities, and disability studies in the humanities. He is a regular contributor to {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "profhacker.com"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Profhacker.com
}}}
, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "BrailleSC.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
BrailleSC.org
}}}
, and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.eighteenthcentury.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
EighteenthCentury.org.
}}}
\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 {\b Hayim Lapin} is the Robert H. Smith Professor of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.jewishstudies.umd.edu/faculty/lapin.html"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Jewish Studies
}}}
 and a Professor in the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.history.umd.edu/Bio/lapin.html"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Department of History
}}}
 at the University of Maryland. He received his PhD from Columbia University. Hayim\u8217's research has been at the intersection of classical Jewish texts (especially legal texts) and social and cultural history. His most recent book is on the development of the rabbinic movement in Palestine in the third and fourth centuries of the Common Era (AD) seen from the perspective of Roman provincial history. His current project, drawing on the same body of literature, is a digital scholarly edition of a principal legal text known as the Mishnah.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 {\b Dr. Ian Bogost} is an award-winning designer and media philosopher whose work focuses on videogames and computational media. He is Ivan Allen College Distinguished Chair in Media Studies and Professor of Interactive Computing at the Georgia Institute of Technology, and Founding Partner at Persuasive Games LLC. His research and writing considers videogames as an expressive medium, and his creative practice focuses on political games and artgames. Bogost is author or co-author of {\i Unit Operations: An Approach to Videogame Criticism}, P{\i ersuasive Games: The Expressive Power of Videogames}, {\i Racing the Beam: The Atari Video Computer System}, {\i Newsgames: Journalism at Play}, {\i How To Do Things with Videogames}, {\i Alien Phenomenology, or What it's Like to Be a Thing}, and {\i 10 PRINT CHR$(205.5+RND(1)); : GOTO 10}. His recent independent games include Cow Clicker, a Facebook game send-up of Facebook games, and A Slow Year, a collection of videogame poems for Atari VCS, Windows, and Mac, and winner of the Vanguard and Virtuoso awards at the 2010 Indiecade Festival. Bogost holds a Bachelors degree in Philosophy and Comparative Literature from the University of Southern California, and a Masters and Ph.D. in Comparative Literature from UCLA. You can follow him on twitter {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "twitter.com/ibogost"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
@ibogost
}}}
.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Janel works in the School of Languages, Literatures and Cultures in the College of Arts & Humanities, where she is both an academic technologist and an instructional designer who works with faculty to explore, create and integrate technology and multimedia resources into their language and literature courses.\u160?She has served as an instructor of Spanish and/or teacher trainer in Harford and Anne Arundel County public schools, Harford Community College, Anne Arundel Community College and Towson University. Janel received her BA in Spanish from {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.naz.edu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Nazareth College of Rochester
}}}
, NY and a M.Ed in Secondary Education & Instructional Technology from Towson University, MD.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 {\b Janet H. Murray} is an internationally recognized interactive designer, the former director of Georgia Tech's Masters and PhD Program in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "dm.gatech.edu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Digital Media
}}}
 (2000-2010), and a member of Georgia Tech's interdisciplinary {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.gvu.gatech.edu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
GVU
}}}
 Center. \u160?She is the author of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.amazon.com/Hamlet-Holodeck-Future-Narrative-Cyberspace/dp/0262631873/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&s=books&qid=1286224623&sr=8-1"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Hamlet on the Holodeck: The Future of Narrative in Cyberspace
}}}
 (Free Press, 1997; MIT Press 1998), which has been translated into 5 languages, and \u160?is widely used as a roadmap to emerging broadband art, information, and entertainment environments,and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "mitpress.mit.edu/catalog/item/default.asp?ttype=2&tid=12666"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Inventing the Medium: Principles of Interaction Design as a Cultural Practice
}}}
 (MIT Press, 2011). Her interactive design projects at include a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "dm.gatech.edu/%7Emurray/casablancaNEHmagazine.pdf"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
digital edition of the Warner Brothers classic,
}}}
 {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "dm.gatech.edu/%7Emurray/casablancaNEHmagazine.pdf"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Casablanca
}}}
, \u160?funded by NEH and in collaboration with the American Film Institute; and the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "intel.gatech.edu"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Interactive Toolkit for Engineering Learning
}}}
 Project, funded by NSF. In addition, she directs the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "etv.gatech.edu"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Experimental Television Laboratory
}}}
, which has worked on interactive television applications for PBS, ABC , MTV, Turner, and other networks. Find her online at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "inventingthemedium.com"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
inventingthemedium.com
}}}
.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Jason Scott is a computer historian and documentary filmmaker who has been collecting, archiving and presenting computer history for over 20 years. Most of his collections can be seen online at the site {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "textfiles.com"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
textfiles.com
}}}
, which began as a small archive of 1980s computer bulletin board history and has expanded to over fifty years of documents and artifacts. Besides presenting at computer conferences and other events, Jason has also shot two documentaries, {\i BBS The Documentary} and {\i Get Lamp}, the second of which covers the text adventure game genre, a precursor to the modern games industry. An outspoken critic of poor data archiving and destruction of digital history, Jason co-founded Archive Team, an activist group of rogue archivists dedicated to saving digital history and gaining attention to the importance of the artifacts online communities. Improbably, he also works for the most popular cat on Twitter, @sockington, who has nearly a million and a half followers.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Before moving to Harvard in 2011,\u160?{\b Jeffrey T. Schnapp}\u160?occupied the Pierotti Chair of Italian Studies at Stanford, where he founded the\u160?Stanford Humanities Lab in 2000._x000D__x000D_ _x000D__x000D_ A cultural historian with research interests extending from antiquity to the present, his most recent books are\u160?Speed Limits and\u160?The Electric Information Age Book (a collaboration with the designer Adam Michaels of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "projectprojects.com/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Project Projects
}}}
\u160?(Princeton Architectural Press, January 2012). Also forthcoming in 2012 are\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "jeffreyschnapp.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/06/Untitled-2.png"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Digital_Humanities\u160?(MIT Press)
}}}
, a book co-written with Anne Burdick, Johanna Drucker, Peter Lunenfeld, and Todd Presner;\u160?Modernitalia (Peter Lang), a collection of essays on 20th century Italian cultural history being edited by Francesca Santovetti, and Italiamerica (Il Saggiatore), vol. 2, co-edited with Emanuela Scarpellini._x000D__x000D_ _x000D__x000D_ His pioneering work in the domains of digital humanities and digitally augmented approaches to cultural programming includes curatorial collaborations with the Triennale di Milano, the Cantor Center for the Visual Arts, the Wolfsonian-FIU, and the Canadian Center for Architecture. His\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.legallerie.tn.it/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Trento Tunnels
}}}
\u160?project \u8212- a 6000 sq. meter pair of highway tunnels in Northern Italy repurposed as a history museum\u8211- was featured in the Italian pavilion of the 2010 Venice Biennale and is currently on exhibit at the MAXXI in Rome in\u160?RE-CYCLE. Strategie per la casa la citt\u224? e il\u160?pianeta\u160?(fall 2011)._x000D__x000D_ _x000D__x000D_ Faculty co-director of the Berkman Center for Internet and Society, he is Professor of Romance Languages & Literature and also on the teaching faculty in the Department of Architecture at Harvard\u8217's Graduate School of Design._x000D__x000D_ _x000D__x000D_ Dr. Schnapp is the faculty director of\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "metalab.harvard.edu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
metaLAB
}}}
\u160?at Harvard.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Jim Casey is a PhD candidate in English at the University of Delaware with research interests in antebellum American print culture and the digital humanities. His dissertation charts the development of editorship and editorial practice in antebellum newspapers. He has served as the co-coordinator of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "coloredconventions.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Colored Conventions Project
}}}
. Read more about Jim on his website {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "jim-casey.com/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
here
}}}
.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Joanna Swafford is the Assistant Professor for Interdisciplinary and Digital Teaching and Scholarship at SUNY New Paltz, specializing in Digital Humanities, Victorian Literature and Culture, Sound, and Gender Studies. Her articles have appeared or are forthcoming in {\i Debates in Digital Humanities}, {\i Journal of Interactive Technology and Pedagogy}, {\i Digital Sound Studies: A Provocation}, {\i Victorian Poetry}, and {\i Victorian Review}, and her book project, {\i Transgressive Tunes: The Politics of Sound in Victorian Poetry}, examines the gendered intermediations of music and poetry. She is the project director for {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.songsofthevictorians.com/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Songs of the Victorians
}}}
, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.augmentednotes.com/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Augmented Notes
}}}
, and Sounding Poetry, and is the co-founder and coordinator of DASH (Digital Arts, Sciences, and Humanities) Lab at SUNY New Paltz. She is also Head of Pedagogical Initiatives for NINES.org (Networked Infrastructure for Nineteenth-Century Electronic Scholarship).\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 _x000D__x000D_ _x000D__x000D_ Kaiama L. Glover\u160?is Associate Professor of French and Africana Studies at Barnard College, Columbia University. Having received a B.A. in French History and Literature and Afro-American Studies from Harvard University and a Ph.D. in French and Romance Philology from Columbia University, Professor Glover joined the Barnard College faculty in 2002. Her teaching and research interests include francophone literature, particularly that of Haiti and the French Antilles; colonialism and postcolonialism; and sub-Saharan francophone African cinema. She advises students in French, Africana Studies, Comparative Literature, and Human Rights. Her book,\u160?{\i Haiti Unbound: A Spiralist Challenge to the Postcolonial Canon}\u160?(Liverpool UP 2010), addresses the general issue of canon formation in the francophone Caribbean and the particular fate of the Haitian Spiralist authors vis-\u224?-vis this canon. She has published articles in\u160?{\i Public Culture},\u160?{\i The French Review},\u160?{\i French Forum},{\i \u160?Small Axe},\u160?{\i Research in African Literatures},\u160?{\i The Journal of Postcolonial Writings}, and\u160?{\i The Journal of Haitian Studies}, among others.\u160?_x000D__x000D_\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 She is the co-editor of "New Narratives of Haiti," a special issue of\u160?{\i Transition}\u160?magazine; co-editor of "Translating the Caribbean," a volume of critical essays on translation in the Americas published as a two-part special section of\u160?{\i Small Axe}; first editor of\u160?{\i Revisiting Marie Vieux Chauvet: Paradoxes of the Postcolonial Feminine}, a volume of critical essays published as a special issue of\u160?{\i Yale French Studies}; and co-editor of the forthcoming Duke University Press\u160?{\i Haiti Reader}. She has translated Frank\u233?tienne\u8217's\u160?{\i M\u251?r \u224? crever}\u160?(Ready to Burst), Ren\u233? Depestre's\u160?{\i Hadriana dans tous mes r\u234?ves}\u160?(Hadriana in All My Dreams), and Chauvet\u8217's\u160?{\i Danse sur le volcan}\u160?(Dance on the Volcano). She has been on the editorial board of the\u160?{\i Romanic Review\u160?}since 2002, on the editorial board of\u160?{\i Small Axe}\u160?since 2012, and since 2016 is the founding co-Editor of\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "smallaxe.net/sxarchipelagos/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
sx archipelagos : a small axe platform for digital practice
}}}
\u160?and co-Director of the digital humanities project\u160?{\i In the Same Boats: Toward an Afro-Atlantic Intellectual Cartography}. She is currently completing a monograph concerning individualism, self-regard, and representations of womanhood in Caribbean prose fiction. Professor Glover has been the recipient of fellowships and awards from the Fulbright Foundation, the Mellon Foundation, The New York Public Library, the PEN/Heim Foundation, the National Endowment for the Arts, and the National Endowment for the Humanities, and she is a regular contributor to\u160?{\i The New York Times Book Review}. She has recently completed a monograph titled "Disorderly Women: On Caribbean Community and the Ethics of Self-Regard."\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 _x000D__x000D_\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Dr. Kim Gallon is an assistant professor of history at Purdue University. She is also the founder and director of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "blackpressresearchcollective.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Black Press Research Collective
}}}
 and an ongoing visiting scholar at the Center for Africana Studies at Johns Hopkins University. Her research focuses on gender and sexuality in the early twentieth century black press. She is also the recipient of several major digital humanities grants to develop digital projects on the black press and create deeper connections between Africana/Black Studies and the digital humanities.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Kimberly Christen-Withey is an Associate Professor and Associate Director of the Digital Technology and Culture program in the Department of English and Director of Digital Projects at the Plateau Center for American Indian Studies at Washington State University. Her work explores the intersections of cultural heritage, traditional knowledge, intellectual property rights, the ethics of openness, and the use of digital technologies in and by indigenous communities globally. She has worked in Tennant Creek, Northern Territory, Australia over the last decade with Warumungu community members on a range of projects including a book, an interactive website, and a community archive. Her collaborations with the Warumungu focused on alliance-making in cross-cultural projects. Her book,\u160?{\i Aboriginal Business: Alliances in a Remote Australian Town}\u160?was published in 2009 by the School of Advanced Research as part of their Global Indigenous Politics Series. Currently she is working on several digital humanities projects that explore the ethical and practical issues of openness and access in relation to indigenous cultural protocols and digital archives. She is the Director of both the\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "plateauportal.wsulibs.wsu.edu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Plateau Peoples' Web Portal
}}}
, a collaboratively curated website of Plateau cultural materials and\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.mukurtu.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Mukurtu CMS
}}}
: an open source indigenous content management system built around the particular needs of indigenous peoples globally. She is also the co-Director of\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.localcontexts.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Local Contexts
}}}
, an educational platform for innovative traditional knowledge licensing systems.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 {\b Lisa Rhody} is a doctoral candidate in the Department of English at the University of Maryland, College Park. Her project \u8220"Review, Revise, Requery: New Methods for Studying Ekphrasis\u8221" was supported by a MITH Winnemore Dissertation Fellowship in Spring 2012.\u160? Find her on the web at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "lisa.therhodys.net"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
lisa.therhodys.net
}}}
 or on Twitter {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "twitter.com/lmrhody"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
@lmrhody
}}}
.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Lori Emerson is Assistant Professor in the Department of English at\u160?the University of Colorado at Boulder. She writes on digital\u160?literature, experimental American and Canadian writing from the 20{\super th} and 21{\super st} century, history of computing, and media theory. You can find\u160?some of her published essays\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "loriemerson.net/curriculum-vitae/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
here
}}}
.\u160?In addition to directing\u160?the\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "mediaarchaeologylab.com/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Media Archaeology Lab
}}}
\u160?she has two forthcoming book projects currently in press. The first is a monograph,\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "loriemerson.net/2012/09/07/reading-writing-interfaces-book-project-description/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
ReadingWriting Interfaces: From the Digital to the Bookbound
}}}
\u160?(forthcoming\u160?from University of Minnesota Press, Spring 2014).\u160?The second is\u160?{\i {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "loriemerson.net/2011/08/10/johns-hopkins-guide-to-digital-humanities/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
The Johns Hopkins Guide to Digital Humanities
}}}
}, co-edited with Marie-Laure Ryan and Benjamin Robertson (forthcoming 2014).\u160?Emerson is also co-editor, with Derek Beaulieu, of\u160?{\i {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.wlupress.wlu.ca/Catalog/beaulieu-emerson.shtml"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Writing Surfaces:\u160?The Selected Fiction of John Riddell
}}}
}\u160?(Wilfred Laurier University Press, 2013)\u160?and co-editor, with Darren Wershler, of\u160?{\i {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.chbooks.com/catalogue/alphabet-game"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
The Alphabet Game: a bpNichol\u160?Reader
}}}
}\u160?(Coach House Books 2007).\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Marisa Parham directs the Five College Digital Humanities Initiative, and is also an associate professor of English at Amherst College. Her teaching and research focus on texts that problematize assumptions about time, space, and bodily materiality, particularly as such terms share a history of increasing complexity in texts produced by African Americans. Her current projects include books and articles on the posthuman, on Octavia Butler\u8217's unpublished work, and on problems of hypertextuality and abstract equivalence in American literature, film, and music. She holds a PhD in English and Comparative Literature from Columbia University, and is the author of\u160?{\i Haunting and Displacement in African-American Literature and Culture}, which you can learn more about at\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "mp285.com/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
her website
}}}
.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 {\b Mark Matienzo} is a Digital Archivist at Yale University Library\u8217's Manuscripts and Archives department and Technical Architect for the ArchivesSpace project. Matienzo served as lead digital archivist for the Andrew W. Mellon Foundation-funded AIMS project (\u8220"Born-Digital Collections: An Inter-Institutional Model for Stewardship\u8221"), a partnership between Yale University, University of Virginia, Stanford University, and University of Hull. He is also an adjunct faculty member at the iSchool at Drexel University, where he teaches digital preservation. He received a Master of Science in Information from the University of Michigan and a BA in Philosophy from the College of Wooster. More information about his projects and research can be found online at\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "matienzo.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
matienzo.org
}}}
.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Mark Priestley is an independent researcher into the history and philosophy of computing, based in London. He studied mathematics and philosophy at the University of Oxford, and started his career as a programmer before working for many years as a lecturer in software engineering at the University of Westminster. He then turned to the history of computing, gaining a PhD in science and technology studies from University College London. His previous book, A Science of Operations: Machines, Logic, and the Invention of Programming (Springer, 2011), explores the influence of logical ideas on the evolution of programming methods. Following on from ENIAC in Action (MIT 2016), he is working on recapturing the details of early programming ideas and practices in other contexts. More information is available at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.markpriestley.net"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
his website
}}}
.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 {\b Professor Mark Sample} teaches and researches contemporary American literature and Digital Culture at George Mason University. His most recent publication, in Game Studies, explores the interplay between video games, the War on Terror, and the production of knowledge. Professor Sample can be found blogging at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.samplereality.com"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
www.samplereality.com
}}}
.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Matthew G. Kirschenbaum is Associate Professor in the Department of English at the University of Maryland and Associate Director of the Maryland Institute for Technology in the Humanities (MITH, an applied thinktank for the digital humanities). He is also an affiliated faculty member with the Human-Computer Interaction Lab at Maryland, and a member of the teaching faculty at the University of Virginia\u8217's Rare Book School.\u160? Kirschenbaum served as the first director of the new Digital Cultures and Creativity living/learning program in the Honors College at Maryland._x000D__x000D_ _x000D__x000D_ A 2011 Guggenheim Fellow, he specializes in digital humanities, electronic literature, virtual worlds, serious games and simulations, textual studies, and postmodern/experimental literature. His first book, {\i Mechanisms: New Media and the Forensic Imagination}, was published by the MIT Press in 2008.{\i Mechanisms} has won the 2009 Richard J. Finneran Award from the Society for Textual Scholarship (STS), the 2009 George A. and Jean S. DeLong Prize from the Society for the History of Authorship, Reading, and Publishing (SHARP), and the 16th annual Prize for a First Book from the Modern Language Association (MLA).\u160? Much of his work now focuses on the critical and scholarly implications of the shift to born-digital textual and cultural production. He was principal investigator for the NEH funded start-up \u8220"Approaches to Managing and Collecting Born-Digital Literary Materials for Scholarly Use\u8221" and is also a co-investigator on the NDIIPP-and IMLS-funded project devoted to Preserving Virtual Worlds (2007 to present). In 2010 he co-authored (with Richard Ovenden and Gabriela Redwine) {\i Digital Forensics and Born-Digital Content in Cultural Heritage Collections}, a report published by the Council on Library and Information Resources and recognized with a commendation from the Society of American Archivists. He also oversees work on the {\i Deena Larsen Collection} at MITH, a vast personal archive of hardware and software furnishing a cross-section of the electronic writing community during its key formative years, roughly 1985-1995. Kirschenbaum serves on the editorial or advisory boards of a number of projects and publications, including {\i Postmodern Culture}, {\i Text Technology}, {\i Textual Cultures}, {\i MediaCommons}, and {\i futureArch}. An avid tabletop gamer, he contributes to the group blog {\i Play the Past} devoted to meaningful play and cultural heritage. His work has received coverage in the {\i Atlantic, New York Times, National Public Radio, Wired, Boing Boing, Slashdot,} and the {\i Chronicle of Higher Education}. See {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.mkirschenbaum.net/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
www.mkirschenbaum.net
}}}
 for more.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Matthew Lincoln is a PhD candidate in Art History at the University of Maryland, College Park, and inaugural recipient of the Arthur K. Wheelock Doctoral Fellowship in Northern European Art. He focuses on sixteenth- and seventeenth-century Dutch and Flemish art, with a particular concentration in the history of prints, and a methodological specialization in digitally-aided analysis. His dissertation uses computational network analysis to explore long-term changes in the organization of print designers, engravers, and publishers in the Netherlands between 1500\u8211-1700._x000D__x000D_ _x000D__x000D_ During the 2014\u8211-2015 academic year, Matthew held the University of Maryland Museum Fellowship at the National Gallery of Art in the Department of Northern Baroque Painting. In the summer of 2015 he will be a fellow at the Harvard MetaLab workshop Beautiful Data, in addition to presenting research at the Alliance for Digital Humanities Organizations' annual international conference in Sydney. In the summer of 2014 he was selected as a Fellow for the Kress Digital Mapping and Art History Summer Institute. Previously, he was a graduate assistant for Digital Humanities at the Michelle Smith Collaboratory for Visual Culture. He has presented research at the Renaissance Society of America, the Sixteenth Century Association, and the College Art Association. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "matthewlincoln.net/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Select talks and projects can be seen on his website.
}}}
_x000D__x000D_ _x000D__x000D_ His MA thesis, \u8220"Hendrick Goltzius\u8217' Protean Iconography: 1582-1590\u8221", investigated the novel and erudite iconographies invented by the famed Dutch engraver during the crucial early years of his career.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Mauricio enjoys playing with code, objects and all things interactive. He has\u160?spent the last fifteen years designing and developing interaction design projects for a wide range of commercial, academic, private and public institutions. Mauricio is an Industrial Designer from Universidad de los Andes in Bogot\u225?, Colombia where he also lectured for six years. He also holds a Master in Human-Computer Interaction from Carnegie Mellon University. \u160?Read more\u160?about Mauricio\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.mauriciogiraldo.com/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
on his website
}}}
.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Maxim Romanov is a research fellow at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.dh.uni-leipzig.de/wo/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Alexander von Humboldt-Lehrstul f\u252?r Digital Humanities
}}}
, Institut f\u252?r Informatik, Universit\u228?t Leipzig. His dissertation (Near Eastern Studies, University of Michigan, 2013) explored how modern computational techniques of text analysis can be applied to the study of premodern Arabic historical sources. In particular, he studied \u8220"The History of Islam\u8221" ({\i Ta\u702?r\u299?\u7723? al-isl\u257?m}), the largest of surviving biographical collections with over 30,000 biographies, written by the Damascene scholar al-\u7694?ahab\u299? (d. 1348 CE). He is continuing his research and develops methods of computational analysis for other genres of premodern Arabic literature, mainly large volume collections that can offer insights into long-term and large-scale developments that took place during the pre-modern period of Islamic history. He is working on two book projects: (1) \u8220"The History of Islam\u8221": An Essay in Digital Humanities continues the study of al-\u7694?ahab\u299?\u8217's tremendous collection of biographies, while (2) The Gift to the Knowledgeable 2.0, explores cultural production in the Islamic world until the beginning of the 20th century through the study of the {\i Hadiyya\u359? al-\u703?\u257?rif\u299?n}, a bibliographical collection composed by Ism\u257?\u703?\u299?l B\u257?\u353?\u257? al-Ba\u289?d\u257?d\u299? (d. 1920).\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Miriam Posner is the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.cdh.ucla.edu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Digital Humanities program
}}}
 coordinator and a member of the core DH faculty at the University of California, Los Angeles. She teaches in the DH program, advises undergraduate and graduate students, and ensures the smooth development of this interdisciplinary program. Prior to joining UCLA, Posner was a Mellon Postdoctoral Fellow at the Emory University Library\u8217's Digital Scholarship Commons. A member of the executive council of the Association for Computers and the Humanities, Posner frequently writes and speaks on digital humanities, as well as on the history of technology, particularly the history of medical imaging. Her book, {\i Depth Perception}, on twentieth-century medical filmmaking, is under contract with the University of North Carolina Press. Her Ph.D., from Yale University, is in Film Studies and American Studies. \u160?You can read more about Miriam {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "miriamposner.com/index.html"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
on her website
}}}
.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Ceruzzi received a BA from Yale University in 1970, and a PhD from the University of Kansas in 1981, both in American studies.\u160?Before joining the National Air and Space Museum, he was a Fulbright scholar\u160?in Hamburg, Germany, and taught History of Technology at Clemson University in Clemson, South Carolina.\u160?Ceruzzi is the author and co-author of several books on the history of computing and aerospace technology. He has curated or assisted in the mounting of several exhibitions at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.orgwiki/National_Air_and_Space_Museum"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
NASM
}}}
, including: Beyond the Limits - Flight Enters the Computer Age, The Global Positioning System - A New Constellation, Space Race, How Things Fly and the James McDonnell Space Hangar of the Museum's Steven F. Udvar-Hazy Center, at Dulles Airport.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Porter Olsen currently serves as a research faculty member at the Maryland Institute for Technology in the Humanities (MITH) where he is the Community Lead on the\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "mith.umd.edu/research/bitcurator/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
BitCurator project
}}}
, a Mellon funded project to bring digital forensics tools and techniques to collecting institutions working with born-digital material. Simultaneously, he is a Ph.D. candidate in the English Department at the University of Maryland studying digital humanities and postcolonial literature._x000D_ _x000D_ His dissertation, titled \u8220"Hacking the Empire: Reading the Digital in Twentieth and Twenty-First Century Postcolonial Literature,\u8221" studies hacker culture in the global south and how the hacker ethos is represented in later 20th\u160?and early 21st\u160?century postcolonial fiction under the direction of Dr. Matthew Kirschenbaum. Porter teaches classes on electronic literature and globalization and has been recognized for his contributions to the growing online teaching program in the university\u8217's English department._x000D_ _x000D_ Before returning to graduate school, Porter worked as product manager on the United Linux initiative, an effort to create a single Linux platform shared among distributors from Germany, Brazil, the U.S., and Japan.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Purdom Lindblad is the Assistant Director of Innovation and Learning at MITH. She\u160?has an MA in American Studies from Michigan State University and an MS in Information Science from the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.si.umich.edu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
School of Information
}}}
, University of Michigan. Interested in digital humanities since graduate school, Purdom has worked at Michigan State University\u8217's {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www2.matrix.msu.edu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Matrix
}}}
, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.lib.vt.edu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Virginia Tech Libraries
}}}
, and the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "scholarslab.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Scholars\u8217' Lab
}}}
 at the University of Virginia Library._x000D__x000D_ _x000D__x000D_ Purdom is broadly interested in the implicit and explicit effort that digital humanities can do for social, cultural, and environmental justice. Applying principles from Feminist Interface Design, Purdom and her Scholars' Lab colleague {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "scholarslab.orgpeople/jeremy-boggs/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Jeremy Boggs
}}}
, explore how the process of feature development and public documentation shape the experience of users and render the theoretical underpinnings of digital work more accessible. Recent publications include {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://digitalpedagogy.commons.mla.orgkeywords/praxis/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Praxis
}}}
, a\u160?keyword in the MLA Commons Digital Pedagogy in the Humanities: Concepts,\u160?Models, and Experiments written with {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "nowviskie.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Bethany Nowviskie
}}}
 and Jeremy Boggs as well\u160?as a forthcoming chapter in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/jentery/mhm"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Making Humanities\u160?Matter
}}}
, edited by Jentery Sayers.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Ravon Ruffin received her M.A. in American Studies with a concentration in Museums and Material Culture. Ravon's primary academic interests include urban sustainability, digital culture and Black feminist discourse as a means to redefine the museum as a community institution. She is co-creator of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "browngirlsmuseumblog.com/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Brown Girls Museum Blog
}}}
, a site to promote the visibility of minority communities as museum professionals, audiences, and creatives. She is currently an independent contractor, and consults for museums and cultural institutions to aid in social media amplification, greater inclusionary practices, and community engagement.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Shannon Mattern is an Associate Professor in the School of Media Studies at The New School. Her research and teaching\u160?address relationships between the forms and materialities of media and the spaces (architectural, urban, conceptual)\u160?they create and inhabit. She writes about libraries and archives, media companies' headquarters, place branding, public\u160?design projects, urban media art, media acoustics, media infrastructures, and material texts. She's the author of {\i The\u160?New Downtown Library: Designing with Communities} (2007) and {\i Deep Mapping the Media City} (2015), both\u160?published by the University of Minnesota Press. You can find her at\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "wordsinspace.net/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
wordsinspace.net
}}}
.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Steph Ceraso is an Assistant Professor of English at the University of Maryland, Baltimore County. Her research and teaching interests are rhetoric and composition, pedagogy, sound studies, and digital media. In addition to coediting a special \u8220"{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "harlotofthearts.orgindex.php/harlot/issue/view/9"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Sonic Rhetorics
}}}
\u8221" issue of {\i Harlot}, her work has appeared in {\i {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "currents.cwrl.utexas.edu/2011/digitallyrical"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Currents in Electronic Literacy
}}}
}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.hastac.orgblogs/stephceraso/2014/02/09/sonic-composing-assignments"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
HASTAC
}}}
, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "soundstudiesblog.com/2012/02/27/the-plasticity-of-listening-deafness-and-sound-studies/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Sounding Out! Blog
}}}
, and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "fembotcollective.orgblog/category/laundryday/feminist-media-production-pt-2/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Fembot Collective
}}}
. Some of her forthcoming essays include \u8220"Re(Educating) the Senses\u8221" (in College English) and \u8220"Sound Practices for Digital Humanities\u8221" (in Provoke! Digital Sound Studies, Duke UP). You can find more about her research, media projects, and teaching\u160?{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.stephceraso.com"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
on her website here
}}}
._x000D_ _x000D_ \u160?\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Born in Baltimore, Maryland in 1957, he became an English major at George Washington University after reading {\i Gravity's Rainbow} by Thomas Pynchon in 1975. He received his PhD from Yale University in 1986. He taught at Yale from 1984\u8211-1990, and then at the University of Texas at Austin and the Georgia Institute of Technology. In 1994 he moved back to Baltimore to teach at the University of Baltimore. As a Professor of Information Arts and Technologies, he formerly taught in the Bachelor of Science in Simulation and Digital Entertainment.\u160?He is also involved in the Master's and Doctoral programs. [{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.orgwiki/Stuart_Moulthrop"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Source: Wikipedia
}}}
]\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 {\b Tara McPherson} is Associate Professor of Critical Studies at the University of Southern California\u8217's School of Cinematic Arts.\u160? She is a core faculty member of the IMAP program, USC\u8217's innovative practice based-Ph.D., and also an affiliated faculty member in the American Studies and Ethnicity Department.\u160? Her research engages the cultural dimensions of media, including the intersection of gender, race, affect and place.\u160? She has a particular interest in digital media.\u160? Here, her research focuses on the digital humanities, early software histories, gender, and race, as well as upon the development of new tools and paradigms for digital publishing, learning, and authorship._x000D_ _x000D_ Her {\i Reconstructing Dixie: Race, Gender and Nostalgia in the Imagined South} (Duke UP: 2003) received the 2004 John G. Cawelti Award for the outstanding book published on American Culture, among other awards.\u160? She is co-editor of {\i Hop on Pop: The Politics and Pleasures of Popular Culture} (Duke UP: 2003) and editor of {\i Digital Youth, Innovation and the Unexpected}, part of the MacArthur Foundation series on Digital Media and Learning (MIT Press, 2008.)\u160?\u160? Her writing has appeared in numerous journals, including {\i Camera Obscura, The Velvet Light Trap, Discourse, and Screen,} and in edited anthologies such as {\i Race and Cyberspace, The New Media Book, The Object Reader, Virtual Publics, The Visual Culture Reader 2.0}, and {\i Basketball Jones.}\u160? The anthology, Interactive Frictions, co-edited with Marsha Kinder, is forthcoming from the University of California Press, and she is currently working on a manuscript examining the digital transformation of the archive as it mutates into the database._x000D_ _x000D_ She is the Founding Editor of {\i Vectors}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.vectorsjournal.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
www.vectorsjournal.org
}}}
, a multimedia peer-reviewed journal affiliated with the Open Humanities Press, and is a founding editor of the MacArthur-supported {\i International Journal of Learning and Media} (launched by MIT Press in 2009.)\u160? She is a widely sought-out speaker on the digital humanities, digital scholarship, and feminist technology studies.\u160? Tara was among the founding organizers of Race in Digital Space, a multi-year project supported by the Annenberg Center for Communication and the Ford and Rockefeller Foundations.\u160? She is on the advisory board of the Mellon-funded Scholarly Communications Institute, has frequently served as an AFI juror, is a core board member of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.hastac.org"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
HASTAC
}}}
 , and is on the boards of several journals and other organizations.\u160? At USC, she co-directs (with Phil Ethington) the new Center for Transformative Scholarship and is a fellow at the Center for Excellence in Teaching. With major support from the Mellon Foundation, she is currently working with colleagues from leading universities and with several academic presses, museums, scholarly societies, and archives to explore new modes of scholarship for visual culture research.\u160?\u160? She is the lead PI on the new authoring platform, Scalar, and for the Alliance for Networking Visual Culture, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "scalar.usc.edu/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
scalar.usc.edu
}}}
.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Thomas Haigh received his Ph.D. in History and Sociology of Science from the University of Pennsylvania after earning two degrees in Computer Science from the University of Manchester. Haigh has published on many aspects of the history of computing including the evolution of data base management systems, word processing, the software package concept, corporate computer departments, Internet software, computing in science fiction, computer architecture, and the gendered division of work in data processing. As well as {\i {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "eniacinaction.com/the-book/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
ENIAC in Action
}}}
} (MIT, 2016) he edited {\i {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.hup.harvard.edu/catalog.php?isbn=9780674055681"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Histories of Computing
}}}
} (Harvard, 2011), a collection of the work of Michael S. Mahoney. He write the \u8220"Historical Reflections\u8221" column for Communications of the Association for Computing Machinery (ACM). His new projects are an reexamination of the wartime Colossus codebreaking machine and a book, {\i Acolytes of Information}, on the history of information systems work in the American corporation. Learn more at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.tomandmaria.com/tom"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
his website
}}}
.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 Zach is\u160?an Associate Professor at the University of Mary Washington where he teaches courses in Digital Studies. This includes topics like electronic literature, video games, graphic novels, transmedia fiction, and writing for digital media. His research focuses on video game history, platform studies, creative coding, and comics. He co-edited\u160?{\i {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.amazon.com/Playing-Past-History-Nostalgia-Video/dp/0826516017/"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
Playing the Past: History and Nostalgia in Video Games
}}}
}\u160?(2008) with Laurie N. Taylor.\par}

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li0 \fi0 {\b Zita Nunes} is Associate Professor of English and Director of the Comparative Literature Program at the University of Maryland. She is the author of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "www.upress.umn.edu/book-division/books/cannibal-democracy"}}{\fldrslt{\ul
{\i Cannibal Democracy: Race and Representation in the Literature of the Americas}
}}}
 and an organizer of the Digital Humanities and African American/African Diaspora Studies Conference.\par}
